review_blob: For me, best winter beer around. Vanilla and other spices somehow makes me think of peanut butter (doesnt sound great for a beer but is)! No non RIS Id rather have a 6 pack of in the winter.
Kind of boring for an Oktoberfest.  Reminds me of a Spaten with a bit of Primator dopplebock. Should be a little lighter, too syrupy. Well rounded example otherwise.

Pours with a fairly thick body and a medium, slightly tan head. Aroma is fantastic, a very rich Octoberfest aroma that is malty and with notes of caramel. As with all duck-rabbit offerings, has a very rich taste. Not the very best of marzen Ive ever had but very solid and a great example of the style.

Pours light amber with a thin head and heavy lacing. Aroma is all hops, quite piney and resiny. Although I prefer IPAs with a bit more malt character, the hop profile is great on this beer. The bitterness doesnt stick around for long, making it much easier to enjoy in quantity. The sweetness of the Munich malt and the Centennial hop flavor make this a very nice IPA.

Pours dark copper with a thick head. Aroma is quite yeasty; you can tell this is a Belgian style. Most forward notes are clove, banana, and bubble gum. Beer is enjoyable overall but lacks some complexity that could make it excellent.

Havent had too many black IPAs so this is difficult to rate. I find the mixture of a stout and IPA to be very enticing. As an IPA, however, I believe the hop bitterness needs to be more prominent than they are in this brew. Outside of being somewhat malt-centric, this is a very nice and enjoyable beer if you forget about it as an IPA.

Pours a light copper color with a full head with pretty heavy lacing. Flavor profile is clean as advertised; malt is subdued and showcases the Simcoe, normally an IPA or DIPA kind of hop. It does well with this style without overwhelming as could be the case.

Pours a very clear, amber with a small, light tan head with heavy lacing. Aroma is toffee with very little hop character. Tastes sweet but not cloyingly so; reminiscent of a Dopplebock due to very little hop character in the taste and aroma. A smooth and enjoyable Barleywine, but is something of a one trick pony with its malt essence not being balanced by hops.

A straw color somewhere between an amber ale and a light lager, this beer has a very nice obvious orange aroma. However, it has an odd astringent aftertaste to it that makes it less enjoyable. Flavor is what I would have wanted from the deScription; it is both orangy and creamy with little to no hop character. Is a bit too much like a higher quality bud light lime with orange substituted
beer_name: Buffalo Bills Orange Blossom Cream Ale

review_blob: At initial glance, Id have to say this beer is overrated due to being in a can. Even for an IPA, its a bit too bitter/resiny to be much better. It is certainly enjoyable, but needs a bit more balance as the Northwest style hops are overwhelming.

Pours syrupy and black with a thin, tan head. A very deep roasted character with some chocolate notes and a strong nose and taste of coffee. Pacific hops give this imperial stout a somewhat different character than more traditionally English hopped examples.
beer_name: Eel River Ravens Eye Imperial Stout

review_blob: This beer is very malt forward with hops playing a relatively small part. Color is that of a pretty dark brown ale. Flavor is potent with a somewhat syrupy quality and a bit of caramel. Nose is mostly from the malt aspect of the beer with some noble hopping showing through. Syrupy character of dopplebocks often put me off, but this one is more subdued and is a good example of the style.

An old favorite of mine. This is an IPA that is approachable yet somewhat unique to me as well. An amber almost red hue and a light, white head make a visually attractive beer. You can tell this is a chewy beer, the hop profile makes it more refreshing than it might otherwise be. Is a very well balanced beer with a piny, resiny hop character with a moderately sweet malt backbone.
Very good and unique beer. It has the refreshing and crisp nature of an IPA but also a a lot of complexity from the Belgian style as well. The best of both worlds in my opinion.

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: A bit one-dimensional for my taste. Although tasty, the intense malt is a bit overwhelming.

Pours a pale copper with a large head that dissipates quickly. The aroma was the biggest letdown, although it had notes of both styles the IPA should have shown through here as aroma is more important to it. Additionally, there was a (for me)light but very unsavory barnyard odor that went beyond belgian or saison. Could have been a bad bottle, hard to say. Beyond that body was generally light and refreshing. The taste generally featured the matly, complex nature of a strong belgian ale, which was appreciated. Overall, an interesting combination of styles that could have been slightly better constructed.

Pours a very dark brown and a small creme, head. Aroma is quite strong with notes of raisin and caramel. Has a thin body with a very obvious presence of alcohol at first sip. Flavor is extremely sweet with no discernible attempt at balance. A good beer at first, but is a challenge to down a half liter because of how cloying it is. Does unfortunately remind me a bit of steel reserve.

Pours a dark golden/light amber with an aggressive, white head. Aroma is of caramel with some banana and is buttery. Taste is relatively clean for the high alcohol content, is not harsh. Perhaps not the most exciting Maibock, but is a solid example and would drink again.

Dark golden color that pours with a large, white head. Aroma is piney with sweet, caramel background. Taste is very mellow for an IIPA, but is not bland by any means. Is a very solid beer, although not necessarily that memorable.
beer_name: Lagunitas A Little Sumpin Extra! Ale

review_blob: Had at a beer tasting. Never had this particular style before...has an interesting spicy character to it, almost like a rye. Beer is well balanced yet somehow it seems that the hop and malt flavor profiles are separate. Would buy for its interesting characteristics.
A very unique beer that drinks more like a strong brown ale with the yeasty, complex character of an abt.
beer_name: Dieu du Ciel Rigor Mortis Abt

review_blob: Pours thin with a small, beige head. Aroma and taste is dominated by coffee. The coffee taste is somewhat balanced by the hops and roasted character of the barley. Would be better if the coffee was more balanced by other aspects and if the body was not quite as thin.

Thin pour with a quickly dissolving head. There is little aroma and the color is a bit darker than the average American lager. This is likely the best mass produced American lager as it quite smooth and has some malty character as opposed to beers like Budweiser and Miller. Taste would indicate less adjuncts used than those beers as well. A great session beer, especially for the price.

Pours with a thick, white head. Color is a peachy-amber with a moderate-high carbonation. Aroma is very piny and resinous. Taste is much more smooth and approachable than the initial aroma would indicate. Although not the most unique or memorable IIPA, it is both balanced and a solid example of the style.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Possibly my favorite from Magic Hat. Reminiscent of a light version of Lagunitas Imperial Red. A strong hop aroma with near IPA levels of hopping. Is quite balanced by fruity and caramel malt flavors. A strong yet balanced brew.

Having a pumpkin ale sampler day. This example did not impress. Mouthfeel is nice and creamy but flavor and aroma were subtle and not what I want from this style. Slightly astringent and a strange aftertaste.
beer_name: Buffalo Bills Americas Original Pumpkin Ale

review_blob: Having a pumpkin sampler night. Very nice aroma, smells just like pumpkin pie. Light brown top and light amber on bottom. Sweet, but balanced taste. On par with dogfish head pumpkin ale.
beer_name: Big Boss Harvest Time Pumpkin Ale

review_blob: Having a pumpkin ale tasting day. This one has almost no aroma despite all the spice added. Little body with a sweet taste. Balanced with a lot of nutmeg noticeable. Probably better than most with food, but is an average pumpkin ale by itself.

Pretty nice pumpkin ale. Spice is slightly over-dominant, but makes for a wonderful aroma. Where this beer needs important is the mouthfeel; could have used a lot more pumpkin to make it less watery and more hearty. Still a top 5 pumpkin ale.

I generally dont prefers lagers, but this is a fantastic example of marzen. A very light, clear amber color with a small head. Aroma is subtle but with sweet, caramel nose. Light taste that is one of that smoothest beers Ive ever had.

Very disappointed by this beer. First off, the appearance was unacceptable. Far too much particulate and much more brown than red coloring. Has a good creaminess and decent body. It most definitely doesnt taste like triple digit IBU (dont think you can get that much IBU with 8.6% alcohol anyways). Would like to see it filtered better and with different hop character.
beer_name: Mad River Double Dread Imperial Red

review_blob: Very intense for a dubbel, dark with strong Belgian character. Pours thick with a large head. Pretty well balanced and overall one of my favorite Belgian ales.
Pretty drinkable, but uninspiring. Dark straw color with very little head. Sam Adams Summer Ale is much superior flavor wise.

A better bock than I was expecting. Very light in color, light golden with some orange tint. Fairly low on aroma and what was there wasnt fantastic. The main issue I had with this beer was the how forward the alcohol is. This is sometimes the case with bocks, but this was a bit too dominant. If they had some better aroma hopping and were able to better mask the alcohol at 7%, would be an excellent beer.

Overall would rate a better beer if it were an amber or a light brown ale. It is very very light in flavor and color for a brown ale and also lacks nut brown qualities, especially in the nose. On the plus side, does have more flavor than the average amber but retains the "drinkability" of a lighter beer.
Draft at WBF. Very solid IPA, just wasnt all that impressed. Might as well have juiced it up a bit and made it an IIPA. Still, refreshing and has some very nice hop character.
Draft at WBF. Very nice and roasty. A very interesting porter, seemed to have more of a roasted barley quality than black patent.
I think the one I had at the WBF was aged in an oak barrel, which may have made it better. Whatever it was, excellent IPA.

Based on the hype, I was actually a little disappointed here. The apperance in particular is top notch and the aroma is also superb. Has a very nice chewy mouthfeel. Its the taste that lets me down a little bit. I think perhaps a different combo of hops might have served better here. I prefer the Weyenbacher Double Simcoe to this really. But I wont complain, just probably wont seek it out again for the price.

Pleasantly surprised by this beer. Although I personally wouldnt buy it, it was probably an average porter if uninspired. Thin mouthfeel, but redeemed itself with very pleasing coffee notes and overall smoothness. One of the better major beer company attempts at a legitimate beer.

I tried non-oaked before this version of the AB. Hoppiness is still definitely present, but the oak adds a creamy flavor and texture that mellows out the hops. Adds some dark color and lots of complexity. Great brew, not hesitate to buy it again!

Vintage 2009. Great aroma, love that the hops can be found here. Nice head and color, somewhat dark copper. Very balanced for a barleywine, perfect amount of hops to counterbalance the maltyness. Definitely better than the Duck Rabbit barleywine. Aging my 2nd one for a bit as Im sure it can be even better!
Light head with a dark ruby/brown color. Intense sweetness needs a bit more hopping for balance. Not much in the aroma department, average barleywine overall.

Probably one of my least favorite from Sam Adams. Sounds great but has a couple of problems. Foremost is its total lack of mouthfeel, feels like water going down. Also, little Belgian characteristic to it. Aroma has decent and taste has ok but was mostly sweet with little complexity. Didnt want a second one.

Overall a pretty tasty beer, although not impressive for a double IPA. Needed more bitter punch up front. Tasted like it was 50 or 60 IBU, when it should have been more like 80. Nice floral and citrus aroma, but needed more head retention.

Pours with a golden, copper color with a very insignificant head. This beer seems undercarbed for the style. That said the taste is slight caramel with basically no hops to it. Finishes very clean and is a very drinkable brew. Overall nice for a lager, as I am normally an ale drinker.

Definitely the best of the Saranac brand. This is a pretty average imperial stout at a great price (got six pack for 8.50!) As has been said it is thin for an imperial stout but the hops do a good job of balancing out the maltyness without overpowering what should be the dominate feature of the beer.
Pretty good beer overall. Loved the nutty notes and smooth taste, one of the best from Saranac. Suffers from almost total lack of aroma, stuck my nose in it and could barely whiff anything.
beer_name: Saranac Seasons Best Nut Brown Lager

review_blob: Really liked the Simcoe hops in this brew. Very balanced IPA, malty character adding a lot to the taste. Great aroma and taste, only the apperance was average with a dark straw cloudy color.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: One of my favorite Magic Hat beers. I like the smokey aspect of it, but it needs to have more hop character to it to be a great beer. Its pretty complex but needs to be cleaner as well.
